body:
I'm running a very simple benchmark with SkiaSharp, see code below. It basically just decodes and encodes a JPEG from and into memory.

Running this in a loop in WSL2 or Windows gives the following times:

```
Decoding took 308ms
Decoding + encoding took 738ms. Size=4198568
```

However, running libjpeg-turbo  from the command line gives

```
peter@STS-RYZEN:~/photos$ time djpeg ~/photo.jpg >/dev/null
real    162ms
```

```
peter@STS-RYZEN:~/photos$ time (djpeg ~/photo.jpg | cjpeg -q 90 >/dev/null)
real    245ms
```

So encoding + decoding is **3 times** slower in SkiaSharp?

It tried encoding and decoding to files, but that doesn't change the factor.

How is this possible? Because Skia uses libjpeg-turbo internally no? 

I'm going to try to debug this, but any help is welcome.

```cs
using System;
using System.Diagnostics;
using System.IO;
using SkiaSharp;

namespace JpegEncodingBenchmark
{
	class Program
	{
		static void Main(string[] args)
		{
			var sw = new Stopwatch();

			Console.WriteLine(Environment.OSVersion);
			
			using var data = SKData.Create(@"/home/peter/photo.jpg");

			for (;;)
			{
				sw.Restart();
				
				SKBitmap bitmap = SKBitmap.Decode(data);
				Console.WriteLine($"Decoding took {sw.ElapsedMilliseconds}ms");

				var outputData = bitmap.Encode(SKEncodedImageFormat.Jpeg, 90);
				Console.WriteLine($"Decoding + encoding took {sw.ElapsedMilliseconds}ms. Size={outputData.Size}");
				
				outputData.Dispose();
				bitmap.Dispose();
			}
		}
	}
}
```
